Biofilm formation is universal for all bacteria. The molecular mechanisms governing this process vary among bacteria, but they all culminate in the synthesis of an extracellular matrix. The composition of the extracellular matrix is complex and variable, even within the same bacterial species when environmental conditions are altered [
,
]. However, one common principle is that the matrix scaffold is built from exopolysaccharide or proteins, which eventually can be interwoven with extracellular genomic DNA [
–
]. The reasons underlying the election of a polysaccharide or protein-based biofilm matrix are not well understood, but an increasing number of studies indicate that proteinaceous scaffolds are more common than previously anticipated. Proteins anchored to the bacterial cell surface can assemble the matrix scaffold through homophilic interactions between identical molecules expressed on neighboring cells or through heterophilic interactions with other surface proteins or with non-proteinaceous cell wall structures [
,
]. Members of this group of proteins include autotransporter adhesins [
–
], carbohydrate-binding proteins [
–
], and cell-wall anchored proteins covalently linked to the peptidoglycan (CWA) [
,
–
]. Another strategy by which proteins can contribute to the formation of the matrix scaffold is through polymerization into functional amyloid fibers. Secreted proteins can assemble to form insoluble fibers with a characteristic cross-β-strand structure, where the β-sheets run perpendicular to the fibril axis [
]. Once polymerized, amyloid fibers constitute a strong platform able to mediate interactions between the neighboring cells and surfaces [
–
]. Examples of amyloid fibers mediating biofilm development include curli pili present in

 Enterobacteriaceae

[
,
], FapC in

 Pseudomonas fluorescens

[
], TasA in

 Bacillus subtilis

[
], the aggregative flexible pili named MTP in the pathogen

 Mycobacterium tuberculosis

[
,
] and phenol soluble modulins (PSMs) in

 Staphylococcus aureus

[
].

To further investigate the mechanism of Bap proteolytic cleavage, we performed western immunoblotting of cell wall extracts of

 S

.

 aureus

V329 grown in LB-glu and LB culture conditions. Results revealed that Bap was proteolytically processed in both media (
), but the cleavage products obtained in LB were unable to form high molecular weight aggregates (
). Western immunoblotting of surface proteins from cells grown in LB-glu extracted at different points of the growth curve showed the presence of degradation bands that increased in number and intensity as bacteria grew (
). Mass spectrometry analysis of the largest processed band confirmed that it corresponded to a degradation product of Bap containing at least the N-terminal region of the protein (
). Interestingly, when bacteria entered stationary phase (OD600nm≈4, pH<5) bands corresponding to full-length and the resulting processed fragments of Bap disappeared from the gel and insoluble aggregates recognized by anti-Bap antibody were readily detectable (
).

